==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|sewen|lang=enm}}, {{term|seowen|lang=enm}}, {{term|sowen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|siwian|sīwian|lang=ang}}, {{term|seowian|sēowian|lang=ang}}, {{term|seowan|sēowan|to sew, mend, patch, knit together, link, unite|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|siwjanan||to sew|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|sīw-||to sew|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|sew||to sew|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|saie|lang=frr}}, {{term|sei||to sew|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|säie||to sew|lang=stq}}, Danish {{term|sy|lang=da}}, Polish {{term|szyć|lang=pl}}, Russian {{term|шить|lang=ru}}, Swedish {{term|sy|lang=sv}}. Related to {{l|en|seam}}.

